    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras enter today\u2019s slate with **Yordan Alvarez** (71.69) and **Trea Turner** (70.89) anchoring the lineup, representing our highest-ceiling plays against favorable pitching environments. **Trea Turner** is particularly vital today, as Pfaadt\u2019s slow delivery cadence provides a clear green light for stolen base attempts, augmenting his already elite floor. While **Yordan Alvarez** faces a tougher test in Castillo, his elite xwOBA of .393 overrides the neutral-to-negative park factors. We are also capitalizing on high-leverage spots with **Kyle Schwarber** (65.10) and **Colt Keith** (64.95), both of whom benefit from positive park adjustments and favorable lineup positioning. The decision to start **Logan O'Hoppe** (64.13) against Williamson is driven by a massive +18% adjustment for the pitcher's skill profile, illustrating our commitment to platoon-leveraged production even in sub-optimal batting orders.\n\nThe most difficult roster decision today was benching **Carson Benge** (36.95), whose projection fell just short of our 40.0 \"Below Floor\" threshold due to a poor platoon matchup against Lopez and a weak lineup spot. Similarly, while we prioritize speed, **Victor Scott II** (36.28) was relegated to the bench; despite his elite sprint speed, his projected performance against a high-hold pitcher like Suarez and a bottom-tier batting order (9th) limits his utility in a 5x5 format where efficient at-bats are paramount. Managers should remain vigilant regarding the lineup status of **Hyeseong Kim**, **Caleb Durbin**, **Josh Smith**, and **Christian Yelich**. Should any of these players drop further down their respective lineups, their already marginal scores\u2014specifically for **Christian Yelich** (40.14) and **Josh Smith** (43.49)\u2014could drop below our floor, necessitating a late-afternoon pivot to ensure we preserve our seasonal game caps.",
